<DOC><DOCNO> AP880321-0291 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 2343EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-Borg-Warner     03-21 0190</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Borg-Warner,0197</SECOND><HEAD>Borg-Warner Sells Credit-Reporting Subsidiary to TRW</HEAD><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Borg-Warner Corp. has sold its credit-reportingsubsidiary, Chilton Corp., to TRW Inc. for about $360 million incash, the companies announced Monday.   Borg-Warner said it sold Dallas-based Chilton, which it acquiredin March 1986 for $252 million, to help pay off debt incurred inits 1987 leveraged buyout.   Borg-Warner went private last year in the buyout led by aMerrill Lynch andamp; Co. unit and must pay off $1.7 billion in debts bythe end of 1988. The buyout, which was engineered to avert ahostile takeover by GAF Corp., left Borg-Warner with total debt ofmore than $4 billion.   TRW Chairman Ruben F. Mettler said in a statement issued inCleveland that the acquisition fits into TRW's previously announcedstrategy of increasing its presence in the commercial informationsystems business.   The sale of Chilton leaves Borg-Warner with interests inchemicals and plastics, automotive parts and security and armoredguard services. Borg-Warner already has divested itself of otherassets, including its BWAC Inc. finance unit and its industrialproducts group, to pay off debt incurred in the buyout.</TEXT></DOC>